NEWCASTLE DISEASE - CZECH REPUBLIC: (CENTRAL BOHEMIA) DOVE
**********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 14 Mar 2016
Source: denik.cz [in Czech, machine trans. Corr SB, edited]
http://boleslavsky.denik.cz/zpravy_region/za-uhyn-hrdlicek-v-libichove-mohl-virus-chovatele-holuby-vystavovat-nebudou-20160314.html


A citizen of Libichova [Dobrovice, Central Bohemia (Středočeský)], has drawn the attention of the Regional Veterinary Administration to mass mortalities of wild turtle doves in the village since the end of February 2016. A sample from the dead birds was sent, in early March 2016, to the State Veterinary Institute, Laboratory, in Prague, where experts identified the deadly pigeon disease as paramyxovirus which is a close relative of the Newcastle disease virus of poultry.

The birds are initially visibly depressed, subsequently suffering from diarrhea and then neurological signs: twisting of the neck, paralysis, loss of balance, and orientation. The neck twisting together with other signs make doves unable to eat. The incubation period is 3 to 5 days.

"The infection is transmitted from wild birds, including turtle doves, to domestic pigeons. Spreading to domestic fowl poultry is difficult, "the Central Veterinary Administration" Director Zdeněk Císař, said in a report.

There are numerous breeders of domestic pigeons whose are based at Dobrovice, but they can prevent the disease by vaccination of their birds.

"Pigeon populations belonging to breeders who exhibit at shows or races, are usually vaccinated. Breeders are currently refraining from showing pigeons, said Milan Hradec , who confirmed the preventive measures of the basic organization of the Czech (Pigeon) breeders Association.

The Veterinary Administration recommended that in case more turtle doves are detected, not to tamper with sick or dead animals, and instead to report the finding to the village officials.

[Byline: Martin Weiss]

