[Avian paramyxovirus 1 (APMV-1; family _Paramyxoviridae_) is the etiologic agent of Newcastle disease. APMV-1 strains maintained in pigeon populations have some antigenic differences from other APMV-1 isolates, and are sometimes called pigeon paramyxovirus type 1 (PPMV-1), which was first reported in racing pigeons in Italy in 1981, and then it became pandemic.

Several Newcastle disease outbreaks in chickens have been attributed to PPMV-1, which makes it a real threat to the poultry industry.

The European turtle dove (_Streptopelia turtur_) is a member of the bird family _Columbidae_, the doves and pigeons. The turtle dove is a migratory species with a southern Palearctic range covering most of Europe and the Middle East and including Turkey and north Africa. For a picture go to https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_turtle_dove#/media/File:European_Turtle_Dove_(Streptopelia_turtur).jpg. - Mod.PMB

Maps of the Czech Republic can be seen at http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/czech.pdf and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4097251,52390. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
